{"ts": "2026-06-08T23:58:09.194979+00:00", "update": {"model": {"messages": [{"type": "ai", "data": {"content": "Now I have a full picture of the project. Let me summarize what I found:\n\n- **Repo structure**: Three sub-projects — `core/` (shared Dart logic), `mobile/` (Flutter app for Android/iOS), and `web/` (AngularDart PWA)\n- The README was written for **Flutter 1.0**, which predates stable Flutter web support\n- The `mobile/` directory is the Flutter project (has `pubspec.yaml` with `flutter` SDK dependency)\n- The `web/` directory is an **AngularDart** project (not Flutter) that uses `webdev`\n- You want **Flutter web** output under `build/web/`, which is the standard `flutter build web` output path\n\nHere are the exact shell commands, in order:\n\n---\n\n### (a) Install / enable Flutter web tooling\n\n```bash\nflutter config --enable-web\n```\n\n> *(Modern Flutter SDKs ship web support out of the box; this just confirms it's enabled. You can verify with `flutter devices` — a \"Chrome\" or \"Web Server\" device should appear.)*\n\n### (b) Fetch dependencies for the project\n\nThe `mobile/` Flutter app has a path dependency on `core/`, so you need to get dependencies for both. From the repo root:\n\n```bash\ncd core && pub get && cd ..\ncd mobile && flutter pub get\n```\n\n*(Or, if using only the `flutter` tool: `cd mobile && flutter pub get` will resolve the `core` path dependency automatically in most Flutter versions.)*\n\n### (c) Produce a release web build under `build/web/`\n\n```bash\ncd mobile && flutter build web --release\n```\n\nThis places the output in **`mobile/build/web/`** (relative to the repo root). The `build/web/` path is relative to the Flutter project directory (`mobile/`).\n\n---\n\n### ⚠️ Important caveat\n\nThis project was written for **Flutter 1.0** (circa 2018–2019), which did **not** support `flutter build web`. To actually build it for web today, you would likely need to:\n\n1. Upgrade the Flutter SDK to a modern stable version 